Bola Bamigbola, Osogbo The Osun State Government on Friday heralded the New Year with massive fireworks in 11 towns, including Osogbo, the state capital. The government said the fireworks display  was aimed at sending a message of hope to the residents who had experienced the adverse effects of the coronavirus pandemic that ravaged the entire world in 2020. Speaking during the fireworks display at the Government House, Osogbo, Governor Adegboyega Oyetola, who was represented by the Commissioner for Youth and Sports, Mr Yemi Lawal, reassured the residents of his administration’s commitment to their welfare. Oyetola, in a statement by his Chief Press Secretary, Ismail Omipidan, also described the government’s resolve to allow the crossover and herald the New Year with fanfare as a necessity to identify with the people of the state and build prosperous years together. He said the exercise was replicated in Ile-Ife, Ilesa, Ikirun, Ila, Ijebu-Jesha, Ede, Iwo, Ejigbo, Ikire and Iragbiji. The governor said, “We are doing this as part of efforts to rekindle our people’s hope and celebrate the New Year in a way that will engender more hope, love, unity, harmony, cohesion and peaceful coexistence. As we all know, Year 2020 had been quite challenging. But with the massive display of fireworks, it is our expectation that the New Year will be full of endless success, fulfilment and accomplishment.” “This is to signify that all hands must be on the deck to collectively rebuild our economy and reposition our state. I want our people to know that we have entered a year of socioeconomic resurrection, massive infrastructural development and prosperity for all.” Copyright PUNCH. All rights reserved. This material, and other digital content on this website, may not be reproduced, published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed in whole or in part without prior express written permission from PUNCH. Contact: theeditor@punchng.com     